  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison has been unable to earn a penny since his two crippling falls. He is very grateful for the Travelers Insurance Company policy that Samuel Joseph May took out in his behalf. He received a letter from the agent of the company &quot;intimating a readiness to make prompt settlement at any time.&quot; He describes his injury and the treatments he has received. Recently, he has been trying &quot;magnetism at the hands of a healing medium (a lady) in Boston, and begin to feel some good effects from it; so that, with the aid of Turkish baths, powerful manipulations, and above all, time, I begin to hope for ultimate deliverance, with no prmanent injury to my arm.&quot; He has done nothing about writing the history of the anti-slavery cause. He never kept a diary and his &quot;memory of persons and events is sadly defective.&quot; He enjoyed reading Samuel Joseph May&apos;s article in the Christian Register. Garrison cannot accept Samuel J. May&apos;s invitation, extended to him and his wife, to visit Syracuse because Mrs. Helen Eliza Garrison is &quot;too helpless to undertake such a journey.&quot; Fanny Garrison Villard is now in Zurich and will soon go to Munich.</subfield>
